# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tianocore-edk
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In computing, **BIOS** or the **Basic Input/Output System** is a type of firmware used to provide runtime services for operating systems and programs and to perform hardware initialization during the booting process (power-on startup).
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] On a computer using BIOS firmware, the firmware comes pre-installed on the computer's motherboard.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The name originates from the **B**asic **I**nput/**O**utput **S**ystem used in the CP/M operating system in 1975.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS firmware was originally proprietary to the IBM PC; it was reverse engineered by some companies, such as Compaq, Phoenix Technologies, AMI and others, looking to create compatible systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The interface of that original system serves as a *de facto* standard.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS in older PCs initializes and tests the system hardware components (power-on self-test or POST for short), and loads a boot loader from a mass storage device which then initializes a kernel.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In the era of DOS, the BIOS provided BIOS interrupt calls for the keyboard, display, storage, and other input/output (I/O) devices that standardized an interface to application programs and the operating system.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] More recent operating systems do not use the BIOS interrupt calls after startup.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Most BIOS implementations are specifically designed to work with a particular computer or motherboard model, by interfacing with various devices especially system chipset.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Originally, BIOS firmware was stored in a ROM chip on the PC motherboard.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In later computer systems, the BIOS contents are stored on flash memory so it can be rewritten without removing the chip from the motherboard.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] This allows easy, end-user updates to the BIOS firmware so new features can be added or bugs can be fixed, but it also creates a possibility for the computer to become infected with BIOS rootkits.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Furthermore, a BIOS upgrade that fails could brick the motherboard.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) is a successor to the legacy PC BIOS, aiming to address its technical limitations.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] UEFI firmware may include legacy BIOS compatibility to maintain compatibility with operating systems and option cards that do not support UEFI native operation.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Intel phased out providing support for booting from the BIOS interface from 2020 to 2024 depending on the platform.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The last version of Microsoft Windows to officially support running on PCs which use legacy BIOS firmware is Windows 10 as Windows 11 requires a UEFI-compliant system (except for IoT Enterprise editions of Windows 11 since version 24H2).
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The term BIOS (Basic Input/Output System) was created by Gary Kildall and first appeared in the CP/M operating system in 1975, describing the machine-specific part of CP/M loaded during boot time that interfaces directly with the hardware.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Versions of MS-DOS, PC DOS or DR-DOS contain a file called variously "IO.SYS", "IBMBIO.COM", "IBMBIO.SYS", or "DRBIOS.SYS"; this file is known as the "DOS BIOS" (also known as the "DOS I/O System") and contains the lower-level hardware-specific part of the operating system.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Together with the underlying hardware-specific but operating system-independent "System BIOS", which resides in ROM, it represents the analogue to the "CP/M BIOS".
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS originally proprietary to the IBM PC has been reverse engineered by some companies, such as Compaq, Phoenix Technologies, AMI and others, looking to create compatible systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] With the introduction of PS/2 machines, IBM divided the System BIOS into real- and protected-mode portions.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS of the original IBM PC and XT had no interactive user interface.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Error codes or messages were displayed on the screen, or coded series of sounds were generated to signal errors when the power-on self-test (POST) had not proceeded to the point of successfully initializing a video display adapter.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Options on the IBM PC and XT were set by switches and jumpers on the main board and on expansion cards.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Starting around the mid-1990s, it became typical for the BIOS ROM to include a *"BIOS configuration utility"* (BCU) or "BIOS setup utility", accessed at system power-up by a particular key sequence.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] This program allowed the user to set system configuration options, of the type formerly set using DIP switches, through an interactive menu system controlled through the keyboard.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In the interim period, IBM-compatible PCs‍—‌including the IBM AT‍—‌held configuration settings in battery-backed RAM and used a bootable configuration program on floppy disk, not in the ROM, to set the configuration options contained in this memory.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The floppy disk was supplied with the computer, and if it was lost the system settings could not be changed.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The same applied in general to computers with an EISA bus, for which the configuration program was called an EISA Configuration Utility (ECU).
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] A modern Wintel-compatible computer provides a setup routine essentially unchanged in nature from the ROM-resident BIOS setup utilities of the late 1990s; the user can configure hardware options using the keyboard and video display.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The modern Wintel machine may store the BIOS configuration settings in flash ROM, perhaps the same flash ROM that holds the BIOS itself.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Peripheral cards such as hard disk drive host bus adapters and video cards have their own firmware, and BIOS extension option ROM code may be a part of the expansion card firmware; that code provides additional capabilities in the BIOS.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Code in option ROMs runs before the BIOS boots the operating system from mass storage.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] These ROMs typically test and initialize hardware, add new BIOS services, or replace existing BIOS services with their own services.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] For example, a SCSI controller usually has a BIOS extension ROM that adds support for hard drives connected through that controller.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] An extension ROM could in principle contain operating system, or it could implement an entirely different boot process such as network booting.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Operation of an IBM-compatible computer system can be completely changed by removing or inserting an adapter card (or a ROM chip) that contains a BIOS extension ROM.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The motherboard BIOS typically contains code for initializing and bootstrapping integrated display and integrated storage.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In addition, plug-in adapter cards such as SCSI, RAID, network interface cards, and video cards often include their own BIOS (e.g., Video BIOS), complementing or replacing the system BIOS code for the given component.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Even devices built into the motherboard can behave in this way; their option ROMs can be a part of the motherboard BIOS.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] An add-in card requires an option ROM if the card is not supported by the motherboard BIOS and the card needs to be initialized or made accessible through BIOS services before the operating system can be loaded (usually this means it is required in the boot process).
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] An additional advantage of ROM on some early PC systems (notably including the IBM PCjr) was that ROM was faster than main system RAM.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Option ROMs normally reside on adapter cards.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The IBM PCjr is unique among PCs in having two ROM cartridge slots on the front.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Cartridges in these slots map into the same region of the upper memory area used for option ROMs, and the cartridges can contain option ROM modules that the BIOS would recognize.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The cartridges can also contain other types of ROM modules, such as BASIC programs, that are handled differently.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] One PCjr cartridge can contain several ROM modules of different types, possibly stored together in one ROM chip.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The 8086 and 8088 start at physical address FFFF0h.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The 80286 starts at physical address FFFFF0h.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The 80386 and later x86 processors start at physical address FFFFFFF0h.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] When the system is initialized, the first instruction of the BIOS appears at that address.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] If the system has just been powered up or the reset button was pressed ("cold boot"), the full power-on self-test (POST) is run.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] If Ctrl+Alt+Delete was pressed ("warm boot"), a special flag value stored in nonvolatile BIOS memory ("CMOS") tested by the BIOS allows bypass of the lengthy POST and memory detection.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The POST identifies, tests and initializes system devices such as the CPU, chipset, RAM, motherboard, video card, keyboard, mouse, hard disk drive, optical disc drive and other hardware, including integrated peripherals.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Early IBM PCs had a routine in the POST that would download a program into RAM through the keyboard port and run it.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] This feature was intended for factory test or diagnostic purposes.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] After the motherboard BIOS completes its POST, most BIOS versions search for option ROM modules, also called BIOS extension ROMs, and execute them.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The motherboard BIOS scans for extension ROMs in a portion of the "upper memory area" (the part of the x86 real-mode address space at and above address 0xA0000) and runs each ROM found, in order.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] To discover memory-mapped option ROMs, a BIOS implementation scans the real-mode address space from `0x0C0000` to `0x0F0000` on 2 KB (2,048 bytes) boundaries, looking for a two-byte ROM *signature*: 0x55 followed by 0xAA.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In a valid expansion ROM, this signature is followed by a single byte indicating the number of 512-byte blocks the expansion ROM occupies in real memory, and the next byte is the option ROM's entry point (also known as its "entry offset").
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] If the ROM has a valid checksum, the BIOS transfers control to the entry address, which in a normal BIOS extension ROM should be the beginning of the extension's initialization routine.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] At this point, the extension ROM code takes over, typically testing and initializing the hardware it controls and registering interrupt vectors for use by post-boot applications.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] It may use BIOS services (including those provided by previously initialized option ROMs) to provide a user configuration interface, to display diagnostic information, or to do anything else that it requires.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] An option ROM should normally return to the BIOS after completing its initialization process.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Once (and if) an option ROM returns, the BIOS continues searching for more option ROMs, calling each as it is found, until the entire option ROM area in the memory space has been scanned.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] It is possible that an option ROM will not return to BIOS, pre-empting the BIOS's boot sequence altogether.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] After the POST completes and, in a BIOS that supports option ROMs, after the option ROM scan is completed and all detected ROM modules with valid checksums have been called, the BIOS calls interrupt 19h to start boot processing.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Post-boot, programs loaded can also call interrupt 19h to reboot the system, but they must be careful to disable interrupts and other asynchronous hardware processes that may interfere with the BIOS rebooting process, or else the system may hang or crash while it is rebooting.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] When interrupt 19h is called, the BIOS attempts to locate boot loader software on a "boot device", such as a hard disk, a floppy disk, CD, or DVD.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] It loads and executes the first boot software it finds, giving it control of the PC.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS uses the boot devices set in Nonvolatile BIOS memory (CMOS), or, in the earliest PCs, DIP switches.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS checks each device in order to see if it is bootable by attempting to load the first sector (boot sector).
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] If the sector cannot be read, the BIOS proceeds to the next device.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] If the sector is read successfully, some BIOSes will also check for the boot sector signature 0x55 0xAA in the last two bytes of the sector (which is 512 bytes long), before accepting a boot sector and considering the device bootable.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] When a bootable device is found, the BIOS transfers control to the loaded sector.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS does not interpret the contents of the boot sector other than to possibly check for the boot sector signature in the last two bytes.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Interpretation of data structures like partition tables and BIOS Parameter Blocks is done by the boot program in the boot sector itself or by other programs loaded through the boot process.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] A non-disk device such as a network adapter attempts booting by a procedure that is defined by its option ROM or the equivalent integrated into the motherboard BIOS ROM.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] As such, option ROMs may also influence or supplant the boot process defined by the motherboard BIOS ROM.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] With the El Torito optical media boot standard, the optical drive actually emulates a 3.5" high-density floppy disk to the BIOS for boot purposes.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Reading the "first sector" of a CD-ROM or DVD-ROM is not a simply defined operation like it is on a floppy disk or a hard disk.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Furthermore, the complexity of the medium makes it difficult to write a useful boot program in one sector.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The bootable virtual floppy disk can contain software that provides access to the optical medium in its native format.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] If an expansion ROM wishes to change the way the system boots (such as from a network device or a SCSI adapter) in a cooperative way, it can use the *BIOS Boot Specification* (BBS) API to register its ability to do so.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Once the expansion ROMs have registered using the BBS APIs, the user can select among the available boot options from within the BIOS's user interface.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] This is why most BBS compliant PC BIOS implementations will not allow the user to enter the BIOS's user interface until the expansion ROMs have finished executing and registering themselves with the BBS API.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Also, if an expansion ROM wishes to change the way the system boots unilaterally, it can simply hook interrupt 19h or other interrupts normally called from interrupt 19h, such as interrupt 13h, the BIOS disk service, to intercept the BIOS boot process.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Then it can replace the BIOS boot process with one of its own, or it can merely modify the boot sequence by inserting its own boot actions into it, by preventing the BIOS from detecting certain devices as bootable, or both.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Before the BIOS Boot Specification was promulgated, this was the only way for expansion ROMs to implement boot capability for devices not supported for booting by the native BIOS of the motherboard.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The user can select the boot priority implemented by the BIOS.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] For example, most computers have a hard disk that is bootable, but sometimes there is a removable-media drive that has higher boot priority, so the user can cause a removable disk to be booted.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In most modern BIOSes, the boot priority order can be configured by the user.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS in an early PC also usually would only boot from the first floppy disk drive or the first hard disk drive, even if there were two drives installed.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] On the original IBM PC and XT, if no bootable disk was found, the BIOS would try to start ROM BASIC with the interrupt call to interrupt 18h.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Since few programs used BASIC in ROM, clone PC makers left it out; then a computer that failed to boot from a disk would display "No ROM BASIC" and halt (in response to interrupt 18h).
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Later computers would display a message like "No bootable disk found"; some would prompt for a disk to be inserted and a key to be pressed to retry the boot process.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] A modern BIOS may display nothing or may automatically enter the BIOS configuration utility when the boot process fails.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The environment for the boot program is very simple: the CPU is in real mode and the general-purpose and segment registers are undefined, except SS, SP, CS, and DL.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] CS:IP always points to physical address `0x07C00`.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] What values CS and IP actually have is not well defined.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Because boot programs are always loaded at this fixed address, there is no need for a boot program to be relocatable.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] DL may contain the drive number, as used with interrupt 13h, of the boot device.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] SS:SP points to a valid stack that is presumably large enough to support hardware interrupts, but otherwise SS and SP are undefined.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] (A stack must be already set up in order for interrupts to be serviced, and interrupts must be enabled in order for the system timer-tick interrupt, which BIOS always uses at least to maintain the time-of-day count and which it initializes during POST, to be active and for the keyboard to work.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] At boot time, all BIOS services are available, and the memory below address `0x00400` contains the interrupt vector table.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] BIOS POST has initialized the system timers, interrupt controller(s), DMA controller(s), and other motherboard/chipset hardware as necessary to bring all BIOS services to ready status.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] DRAM refresh for all system DRAM in conventional memory and extended memory, but not necessarily expanded memory, has been set up and is running.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS maintains a reserved block of system RAM at addresses `0x00400–0x004FF` with various parameters initialized during the POST.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] All memory at and above address `0x00500` can be used by the boot program; it may even overwrite itself.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS ROM is customized to the particular manufacturer's hardware, allowing low-level services (such as reading a keystroke or writing a sector of data to diskette) to be provided in a standardized way to programs, including operating systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] For example, an IBM PC might have either a monochrome or a color display adapter (using different display memory addresses and hardware), but a single, standard, BIOS system call may be invoked to display a character at a specified position on the screen in text mode or graphics mode.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS provides a small library of basic input/output functions to operate peripherals (such as the keyboard, rudimentary text and graphics display functions and so forth).
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Operating systems and executive software that are designed to supersede this basic firmware functionality provide replacement software interfaces to application software.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Applications can also provide these services to themselves.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] This began even in the 1980s under MS-DOS, when programmers observed that using the BIOS video services for graphics display were very slow.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] To increase the speed of screen output, many programs bypassed the BIOS and programmed the video display hardware directly.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Other graphics programmers, particularly but not exclusively in the demoscene, observed that there were technical capabilities of the PC display adapters that were not supported by the IBM BIOS and could not be taken advantage of without circumventing it.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Since the AT-compatible BIOS ran in Intel real mode, operating systems that ran in protected mode on 286 and later processors required hardware device drivers compatible with protected mode operation to replace BIOS services.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Modern operating systems, such as Windows and Linux, use the BIOS interrupt calls only during the booting process.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Before the operating system's first graphical screen is displayed, input and output are typically handled through BIOS.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] A boot menu such as the textual menu of Windows, which allows users to choose an operating system to boot, to boot into the safe mode, or to use the last known good configuration, is displayed through BIOS and receives keyboard input through BIOS.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Many modern PCs can still boot and run legacy operating systems such as MS-DOS or DR-DOS that rely heavily on BIOS for their console and disk I/O, providing that the system has a BIOS, or a CSM-capable UEFI firmware.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Intel processors have reprogrammable microcode since the P6 microarchitecture.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] AMD processors have reprogrammable microcode since the K7 microarchitecture.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS contains patches to the processor microcode that fix errors in the initial processor microcode; microcode is loaded into processor's SRAM so reprogramming is not persistent, thus loading of microcode updates is performed each time the system is powered up.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Without reprogrammable microcode, an expensive processor swap would be required; for example, the Pentium FDIV bug became an expensive fiasco for Intel as it required a product recall because the original Pentium processor's defective microcode could not be reprogrammed.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Operating systems can also update the microcode.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Some BIOSes contain a software licensing description table (SLIC), a digital signature placed inside the BIOS by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM), for example Dell.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The SLIC is inserted into the ACPI data table and contains no active code.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Computer manufacturers that distribute OEM versions of Microsoft Windows and Microsoft application software can use the SLIC to authenticate licensing to the OEM Windows Installation disk and system recovery disc containing Windows software.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Systems with a SLIC can be preactivated with an OEM product key, and they verify an XML formatted OEM certificate against the SLIC in the BIOS as a means of self-activating (see System Locked Preinstallation, SLP).
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] If a user performs a fresh install of Windows, they will need to have possession of both the OEM key (either SLP or COA) and the digital certificate for their SLIC in order to bypass activation.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] This can be achieved if the user performs a restore using a pre-customised image provided by the OEM.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Power users can copy the necessary certificate files from the OEM image, decode the SLP product key, then perform SLP activation manually.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Some BIOS implementations allow overclocking, an action in which the CPU is adjusted to a higher clock rate than its manufacturer rating for guaranteed capability.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Overclocking may, however, seriously compromise system reliability in insufficiently cooled computers and generally shorten component lifespan.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Overclocking, when incorrectly performed, may also cause components to overheat so quickly that they mechanically destroy themselves.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Some older operating systems, for example MS-DOS, rely on the BIOS to carry out most input/output tasks within the PC.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Calling real mode BIOS services directly is inefficient for protected mode (and long mode) operating systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] BIOS interrupt calls are not used by modern multitasking operating systems after they initially load.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In the 1990s, BIOS provided some protected mode interfaces for Microsoft Windows and Unix-like operating systems, such as Advanced Power Management (APM), Plug and Play BIOS, Desktop Management Interface (DMI), VESA BIOS Extensions (VBE), e820 and MultiProcessor Specification (MPS).
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Starting from the year 2000, most BIOSes provide ACPI, SMBIOS, VBE and e820 interfaces for modern operating systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] After operating systems load, the System Management Mode code is still running in SMRAM.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Since 2010, BIOS technology is in a transitional process toward UEFI.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Historically, the BIOS in the IBM PC and XT had no built-in user interface.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS versions in earlier PCs (XT-class) were not software configurable; instead, users set the options via DIP switches on the motherboard.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Later computers, including most IBM-compatibles with 80286 CPUs, had a battery-backed nonvolatile BIOS memory (CMOS RAM chip) that held BIOS settings.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] These settings, such as video-adapter type, memory size, and hard-disk parameters, could only be configured by running a configuration program from a disk, not built into the ROM.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] A special "reference diskette" was inserted in an IBM AT to configure settings such as memory size.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Early BIOS versions did not have passwords or boot-device selection options.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS was hard-coded to boot from the first floppy drive, or, if that failed, the first hard disk.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Access control in early AT-class machines was by a physical keylock switch (which was not hard to defeat if the computer case could be opened).
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Anyone who could switch on the computer could boot it.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Later, 386-class computers started integrating the BIOS setup utility in the ROM itself, alongside the BIOS code; these computers usually boot into the BIOS setup utility if a certain key or key combination is pressed, otherwise the BIOS POST and boot process are executed.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] A modern BIOS setup utility has a text user interface (TUI) or graphical user interface (GUI) accessed by pressing a certain key on the keyboard when the PC starts.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Usually, the key is advertised for short time during the early startup, for example "Press DEL to enter Setup".
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The actual key depends on specific hardware.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The settings key is most often Delete (Acer, ASRock, Asus PC, ECS, Gigabyte, MSI, Zotac) and F2 (Asus motherboard, Dell, Lenovo laptop, Origin PC, Samsung, Toshiba), but it can also be F1 (Lenovo desktop) and F10 (HP).
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] A modern BIOS setup screen often features a **PC Health Status** or a **Hardware Monitoring** tab, which directly interfaces with a Hardware Monitor chip of the mainboard.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] This makes it possible to monitor CPU and chassis temperature, the voltage provided by the power supply unit, as well as monitor and control the speed of the fans connected to the motherboard.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Some operating systems, like NetBSD with envsys and OpenBSD with sysctl hw.sensors, feature integrated interfacing with hardware monitors.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] However, in some circumstances, the BIOS also provides the underlying information about hardware monitoring through ACPI, in which case, the operating system may be using ACPI to perform hardware monitoring.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In modern PCs the BIOS is stored in rewritable EEPROM or NOR flash memory, allowing the contents to be replaced and modified.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] This rewriting of the contents is sometimes termed *flashing.* It can be done by a special program, usually provided by the system's manufacturer, or at POST, with a BIOS image in a hard drive or USB flash drive.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] A file containing such contents is sometimes termed "a BIOS image".
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] A BIOS might be reflashed in order to upgrade to a newer version to fix bugs or provide improved performance or to support newer hardware.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Some computers also support updating the BIOS via an update floppy disk or a special partition on the hard drive.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The original IBM PC BIOS (and cassette BASIC) was stored on mask-programmed read-only memory (ROM) chips in sockets on the motherboard.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] ROMs could be replaced, but not altered, by users.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] To allow for updates, many compatible computers used re-programmable BIOS memory devices such as EPROM, EEPROM and later flash memory (usually NOR flash) devices.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] According to Robert Braver, the president of the BIOS manufacturer Micro Firmware, **Flash BIOS** chips became common around 1995 because the electrically erasable PROM (EEPROM) chips are cheaper and easier to program than standard ultraviolet erasable PROM (EPROM) chips.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Flash chips are programmed (and re-programmed) in-circuit, while EPROM chips need to be removed from the motherboard for re-programming.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] BIOS versions are upgraded to take advantage of newer versions of hardware and to correct bugs in previous revisions of BIOSes.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Beginning with the IBM AT, PCs supported a hardware clock settable through BIOS.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] It had a century bit which allowed for manually changing the century when the year 2000 happened.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Most BIOS revisions created in 1995 and nearly all BIOS revisions in 1997 supported the year 2000 by setting the century bit automatically when the clock rolled past midnight, 31 December 1999.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The first flash chips were attached to the ISA bus.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Starting in 1998, the BIOS flash moved to the LPC bus, following a new standard implementation known as "firmware hub" (FWH).
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In 2005, the BIOS flash memory moved to the SPI bus.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The size of the BIOS, and the capacity of the ROM, EEPROM, or other media it may be stored on, has increased over time as new features have been added to the code; BIOS versions now exist with sizes up to 32 megabytes.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] For contrast, the original IBM PC BIOS was contained in an 8 KB mask ROM.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Some modern motherboards are including even bigger NAND flash memory ICs on board which are capable of storing whole compact operating systems, such as some Linux distributions.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] For example, some ASUS notebooks included Splashtop OS embedded into their NAND flash memory ICs.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] However, the idea of including an operating system along with BIOS in the ROM of a PC is not new; in the 1980s, Microsoft offered a ROM option for MS-DOS, and it was included in the ROMs of some PC clones such as the Tandy 1000 HX.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Another type of firmware chip was found on the IBM PC AT and early compatibles.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In the AT, the keyboard interface was controlled by a microcontroller with its own programmable memory.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] On the IBM AT, that was a 40-pin socketed device, while some manufacturers used an EPROM version of this chip which resembled an EPROM.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] This controller was also assigned the A20 gate function to manage memory above the one-megabyte range; occasionally an upgrade of this "keyboard BIOS" was necessary to take advantage of software that could use upper memory.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The BIOS may contain components such as the Memory Reference Code (MRC), which is responsible for the memory initialization (e.g.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Modern BIOS includes Intel Management Engine or AMD Platform Security Processor firmware.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] IBM published full listings of the BIOSes for its original PC, PC XT, PC AT, and other contemporary PC models, in an appendix of the *IBM PC Technical Reference Manual* for each machine type.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] A benefit of the publication of the BIOS listings is that users could see exactly what the BIOS does and how it does it.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] However, those BIOSes were still copyright by IBM, so they could not be used by other manufacturers.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In March 1983, Compaq released its Compaq Portable, which included a clean-room engineered BIOS.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] This made Compaq became the first company that cloned an IBM PC successfully.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] However, Compaq did not offer their BIOS to other computer manufacturers.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In May 1984, Phoenix Software Associates released its first ROM-BIOS.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] This BIOS enabled OEMs to build essentially fully compatible clones without having to reverse-engineer the IBM PC BIOS themselves, as Compaq had done for the Portable; it also helped fuel the growth in the PC-compatibles industry and sales of non-IBM versions of DOS.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The first American Megatrends (AMI) BIOS was released in 1986.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] New standards grafted onto the BIOS are usually without complete public documentation or any BIOS listings.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] As a result, it is not as easy to learn the intimate details about the many non-IBM additions to BIOS as about the core BIOS services.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Many PC motherboard suppliers licensed the BIOS "core" and toolkit from a commercial third party, known as an "independent BIOS vendor" or IBV.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The motherboard manufacturer then customized this BIOS to suit its own hardware.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] For this reason, updated BIOSes are normally obtained directly from the motherboard manufacturer.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Major IBVs included American Megatrends (AMI), Insyde Software, Phoenix Technologies, and Byosoft.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Microid Research and Award Software were acquired by Phoenix Technologies in 1998; Phoenix later phased out the Award brand name (although Award Software is still credited in AwardBIOS versions until 2001–2002, and AWRDACPI is still credited in Phoenix UEFI firmwares until late 2012).
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] General Software, which was also acquired by Phoenix in 2007, sold BIOS for embedded systems based on Intel processors.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] SeaBIOS is an open-source BIOS implementation.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The open-source community increased their effort to develop a replacement for proprietary BIOSes and their future incarnations with open-sourced counterparts.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Open Firmware was an early attempt to make an open specification for boot firmware.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] It was initially endorsed by IEEE in its *IEEE 1275-1994* standard but was withdrawn in 2005.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Later examples include the OpenBIOS, coreboot and libreboot projects.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] AMD provided product specifications for some chipsets using coreboot, and Google is sponsoring the project.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Motherboard manufacturer Tyan offers coreboot next to the standard BIOS with their Opteron line of motherboards.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] EEPROM and flash memory chips are advantageous because they can be easily updated by the user; it is customary for hardware manufacturers to issue BIOS updates to upgrade their products, improve compatibility and remove bugs.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] However, this advantage had the risk that an improperly executed or aborted BIOS update could render the computer or device unusable.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] To avoid these situations, more recent BIOSes use a "boot block"; a portion of the BIOS which runs first and must be updated separately.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] This code verifies if the rest of the BIOS is intact (using hash checksums or other methods) before transferring control to it.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] If the boot block detects any corruption in the main BIOS, it will typically warn the user that a recovery process must be initiated by booting from removable media (floppy, CD or USB flash drive) so the user can try flashing the BIOS again.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Some motherboards have a *backup* BIOS (sometimes referred as DualBIOS) to recover from BIOS corruptions, and they use a special PLC to do BIOS recovery from BIOS corruptions.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] There are at least five known viruses that attack the BIOS, two of which were for demonstration purposes.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The first one found in the wild was *Mebromi*, targeting Chinese users.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The first BIOS virus was BIOS Meningitis, which instead of erasing BIOS chips it infected them.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] BIOS Meningitis was relatively harmless, compared to a virus like CIH.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The second BIOS virus was CIH, also known as the "Chernobyl Virus", which was able to erase flash ROM BIOS content on compatible chipsets.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] CIH appeared in mid-1998 and became active in April 1999.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Often, infected computers could no longer boot, and people had to remove the flash ROM IC from the motherboard and reprogram it.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] CIH targeted the then-widespread Intel i430TX motherboard chipset and took advantage of the fact that the Windows 9x operating systems, also widespread at the time, allowed direct hardware access to all programs.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Modern systems are not vulnerable to CIH because of a variety of chipsets being used which are incompatible with the Intel i430TX chipset, and also other flash ROM IC types.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] There is also extra protection from accidental BIOS rewrites in the form of boot blocks which are protected from accidental overwrite or dual BIOS equipped systems which may, in the event of a crash, use a backup BIOS.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Also, all modern operating systems such as FreeBSD, Linux, macOS, Windows NT-based Windows OS like Windows 2000, Windows XP and newer, do not allow user-mode programs to have direct hardware access using a hardware abstraction layer.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] As a result, as of 2008, CIH has become essentially harmless, at worst causing annoyance by infecting executable files and triggering antivirus software.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Other BIOS viruses remain possible, however; since most Windows home users without Windows Vista/7's UAC run all applications with administrative privileges, a modern CIH-like virus could in principle still gain access to hardware without first using an exploit.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The operating system OpenBSD prevents all users from having this access and the grsecurity patch for the Linux kernel also prevents this direct hardware access by default, the difference being an attacker requiring a much more difficult kernel level exploit or reboot of the machine.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The third BIOS virus was a technique presented by John Heasman, principal security consultant for UK-based Next-Generation Security Software.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In 2006, at the Black Hat Security Conference, he showed how to elevate privileges and read physical memory, using malicious procedures that replaced normal ACPI functions stored in flash memory.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The fourth BIOS virus was a technique called "Persistent BIOS infection." It appeared in 2009 at the CanSecWest Security Conference in Vancouver, and at the SyScan Security Conference in Singapore.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Researchers Anibal Sacco and Alfredo Ortega, from Core Security Technologies, demonstrated how to insert malicious code into the decompression routines in the BIOS, allowing for nearly full control of the PC at start-up, even before the operating system is booted.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The proof-of-concept does not exploit a flaw in the BIOS implementation, but only involves the normal BIOS flashing procedures.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Thus, it requires physical access to the machine, or for the user to be root.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Despite these requirements, Ortega underlined the profound implications of his and Sacco's discovery: "We can patch a driver to drop a fully working rootkit.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Mebromi is a trojan which targets computers with AwardBIOS, Microsoft Windows, and antivirus software from two Chinese companies: Rising Antivirus and Jiangmin KV Antivirus.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Mebromi installs a rootkit which infects the Master boot record.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In a December 2013 interview with *60 Minutes*, Deborah Plunkett, Information Assurance Director for the US National Security Agency claimed the NSA had uncovered and thwarted a possible BIOS attack by a foreign nation state, targeting the US financial system.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The program cited anonymous sources alleging it was a Chinese plot.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] However follow-up articles in *The Guardian,* *The Atlantic,* *Wired* and *The Register* refuted the NSA's claims.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Newer Intel platforms have Intel Boot Guard (IBG) technology enabled, this technology will check the BIOS digital signature at startup, and the IBG public key is fused into the PCH.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) supplements the BIOS in many new machines.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Initially written for the Intel Itanium architecture, UEFI is now available for x86 and Arm platforms; the specification development is driven by the Unified EFI Forum, an industry special interest group.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] EFI booting has been supported in only Microsoft Windows versions supporting GPT, the Linux kernel 2.6.1 and later, and macOS on Intel-based Macs.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] As of 2014, new PC hardware predominantly ships with UEFI firmware.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] The architecture of the rootkit safeguard can also prevent the system from running the user's own software changes, which makes UEFI controversial as a legacy BIOS replacement in the open hardware community.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] UEFI is required for devices shipping with Windows 8 and above.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Likewise, Windows 11 requires UEFI to boot, with the exception of IoT Enterprise editions of Windows 11.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] After the popularity of UEFI in 2010s, the older BIOS that supported BIOS interrupt calls was renamed to "legacy BIOS".
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Other alternatives to the functionality of the "Legacy BIOS" in the x86 world include coreboot and libreboot.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Some servers and workstations use a platform-independent Open Firmware (IEEE-1275) based on the Forth programming language; it is included with Sun's SPARC computers, IBM's RS/6000 line, and other PowerPC systems such as the CHRP motherboards, along with the x86-based OLPC XO-1.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] As of at least 2015, Apple has removed legacy BIOS support from the UEFI monitor in Intel-based Macs.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] As such, the BIOS utility no longer supports the legacy option, and prints "Legacy mode not supported on this system".
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] In 2017, Intel announced that it would remove legacy BIOS support by 2020.
[src:tianocore-edk/bios] Since 2019, new Intel platform OEM PCs no longer support the legacy option.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] Upon power up, hardware usually starts uninitialized.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] To continue booting, the system may need to read a bootloader from some peripheral device, usually a data storage device.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] It is often easier to implement routines for reading from external storage devices in software than in hardware.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] A boot ROM provides a place to store this initial loading code, at a fixed location immediately available to the processor when execution starts.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] The boot ROM is mapped into memory at a fixed location, and the processor is designed to start executing from this location after reset, according to the processor's reset vector.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] The boot ROM is either placed on the same die as the CPU or is an external ROM chip.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] On modern systems, the boot ROM (whether integrated into CPU or external ROM chip) usually uses NOR flash, which supports execute in place.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] The boot ROM will then initialize the hardware busses and peripherals needed to boot.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] In some cases, the boot ROM is capable of initializing DRAM, and in other cases it is up to the bootloader to do that.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] On some modern ARM CPUs, the boot ROM integrated in CPU will initialize DRAM and then load a bootloader; but after a bootloader (such as Das U-Boot) is loaded, the bootloader may reinitialize DRAM, to fix bugs and reduce cost.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] In many systems on a chip (SoC), the peripherals or buses from which the boot ROM tries to load the bootloader, and the order in which they are loaded, can be configured.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] This configuration can be done by blowing some electronic fuses inside the system on a chip to encode that information, or by having specific pins or jumpers of the system on a chip high or low.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] Some boot ROMs are capable of checking the digital signature of the bootloader and will refuse to run the bootloader and stop the boot if the signature is not valid or has not been signed with an authorized key.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] With some boot ROMs, the hash of the public key needed to verify the signatures is encoded in OTP electronic fuses inside the SoC.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] That feature can then be used to implement security features or used as a hardware root of trust in a chain of trust, but once configured, users are denied the freedom to replace the bootloader with the one they want without the use of boot ROM exploits.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] Because of this, the feature has raised strong concerns from the free software community.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] Just before jumping to the bootloader, some systems on a chip also remove the boot ROM from the memory mapping, while others do not, making it possible to dump the boot ROM for later analysis.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] If the boot ROM is still accessible, bootloaders can also call the code of the boot ROM (which is sometimes documented).
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] When a system on a chip (SoC) enters suspend-to-RAM mode, in many cases, the processor is completely off while the RAM is put in self-refresh mode.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] At resume, the boot ROM is executed again and many boot ROMs are able to detect that the SoC was in suspend-to-RAM mode and can resume by jumping directly to the kernel which then takes care of powering on again the peripherals which were off and restoring the state that the computer was in before.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] On many Allwinner systems on a chip (A10, A20, A64), the boot ROM either waits for a bootloader to be loaded through USB (if a specific PIN is high) or tries to boot on several peripherals in a fixed order.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] Some Allwinner systems on a chip can verify the signature of the booloaders.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] But most devices being manufactured are not configured for that.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] This has enabled free and open-source software to add support for many Allwinner systems on a chip and devices using them in bootloaders like U-Boot.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] On iPhone, iPad, Apple Watch, iPod Touch, and Apple TV devices, the boot ROM is called "SecureROM" It is a stripped-down version of iBoot.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] It provides a Device Firmware Upgrade (DFU) mechanism, which can be activated using a special button combination.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] On older IBM PC compatible computers, the BIOS serves as a boot ROM.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] The boot ROM of NXP systems on a chip (SOCs) support configuring the peripherals through specific pins of the system on a chip.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] On the i.MX6 family it also supports configuring the boot order through eFuses.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] The boot ROM of several NXP SoCs have many ways to load the first stage bootloader (from eMMC, microSD, USB, etc.).
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] Several NXP SoCs can be configured to verify the signature of the bootloaders.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] Many devices with such SoCs were sold without that verification configured and on those devices users can install the bootloader they want, including several free and open-source software bootloaders like Das U-Boot and Barebox.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] Open Firmware serves as a boot ROM in systems such as later SPARC-based machines from Sun Microsystems and PowerPC-based Macs.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] STMicroelectronics STM32 family microcontrollers have embedded ROM (also referred as "on-chip ROM") called *system memory* to facilitate empty system flashing.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] Certain pin combinations or sometimes efuses and/or empty flash checks force the chip to boot from ROM instead of the firmware in main flash.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] This allows empty chips to be flashed without resorting to hardware programming interfaces.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] Technically this ROM is stored in a dedicated area of the flash array and programmed by ST during production.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] Most STM32 microcontrollers can at least be flashed over UART, some support USB and eventually other interfaces like e.g.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] The Cortex-M core normally fetches vectors from the well-known addresses 0x00000000 (initial stack pointer value) and 0x00000004 (initial program counter value).
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] However pins and/or fuses define which memory is mapped at these addresses.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] System memory is one of the mapping options, another would typically be main firmware in flash.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] In this case, firmware is supposed to do all the jobs boot ROMs do; part of the firmware could act as a bootloader similar to ST's boot ROM.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] Hardware could provide read-only enforcement on the boot area, turning it into a user-provided version of boot ROM.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] The boot ROMs of several Texas Instruments systems on a chip support configuring the peripherals through specific pins of the system on a chip.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] On the OMAP36xx system on a chip, the boot ROM looks for the first stage bootloader at the sectors 0x0 and 0x20000 (128KB), and on the AM3358 system on a chip, it additionally looks at 0x40000 (256KiB) and 0x60000 (384KiB).
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] In both cases its maximum size is 128KiB.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] This is because the (first stage) bootloader is loaded in an SRAM that is inside the system on a chip.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] The OMAP and AM335x systems on a chip can be configured to verify the signature of the bootloaders.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] Many devices with such system on a chip were sold without verification configured and on those devices users can install the bootloader they want, including several free and open-source software bootloaders like Das U-Boot and Coreboot and Barebox.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] UEFI serves as a boot ROM on systems such as newer IBM PC compatible computers.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] On devices running iOS, boot ROM exploits (like the limera1n, alloc8, and checkm8 exploits) are sometimes used for iOS jailbreaking.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] The advantage for people wanting to jailbreak their devices over exploits that affect iOS is that since the boot ROM cannot be modified—and that devices running iOS do not have fuses to append code to the boot ROM, Apple cannot fix the vulnerability on existing devices.
[src:tianocore-edk/boot-rom] The boot ROM of the Tegra SoC of Nvidia (used by the Nintendo Switch) contained a vulnerability which made it possible for users to run the bootloader they want.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] In computing, **firmware** (**FW**) is software that provides low-level control of computer hardware.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] For a relatively simple device, firmware may perform all control, monitoring and data manipulation functionality.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] For a more complex device, firmware may provide only relatively low-level control as well as hardware abstraction to higher-level software such as an operating system.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Firmware is found in a wide range of computing devices, including personal computers, smartphones, home appliances, vehicles, computer peripherals and in many of the integrated circuits inside each of these larger systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Firmware is stored in non-volatile memory – either read-only memory (ROM) or programmable memory such as EPROM, EEPROM, or flash.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Changing a device's firmware stored in ROM requires physically replacing the memory chip or the device itself.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Programmable firmware memory can be reprogrammed via a procedure sometimes called *flashing*.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Common reasons for changing firmware include fixing bugs and adding features.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Ascher Opler used the term *firmware* in a 1967 *Datamation* article, as an intermediary term between *hardware* and *software*.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Opler projected that fourth-generation computer systems would have a writable control store (a small specialized high-speed memory) into which microcode firmware would be loaded.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Many software functions would be moved to microcode, and instruction sets could be customized, with different firmware loaded for different instruction sets.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] As computers began to increase in complexity, it became clear that various programs needed to first be initiated and run to provide a consistent environment necessary for running more complex programs at the user's discretion.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] This required programming the computer to run those programs automatically.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Furthermore, as companies, universities, and marketers wanted to sell computers to laypeople with little technical knowledge, greater automation became necessary to allow a layperson to easily run programs for practical purposes.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] This gave rise to a kind of software that a user would not consciously run, and it led to software that a lay user would not even know about.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] As originally used, firmware contrasted with hardware (the CPU itself) and software (normal instructions executing on a CPU).
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] It was not composed of CPU machine instructions, but of lower-level microcode involved in the implementation of machine instructions.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] It existed on the boundary between hardware and software; thus the name *firmware*.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] In some respects, the various firmware components are as important as the operating system in a working computer.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] However, unlike most modern operating systems, firmware rarely has a well-evolved automatic mechanism of updating itself to fix any functionality issues detected after shipping the unit.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] A computer's firmware may be manually updated by a user via a small utility program.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] In contrast, firmware in mass storage devices (hard-disk drives, optical disc drives, flash memory storage e.g., solid state drive) is less frequently updated, even when flash memory (rather than ROM, EEPROM) storage is used for the firmware.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Most computer peripherals are themselves special-purpose computers.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Devices such as printers, scanners, webcams, and USB flash drives have internally-stored firmware; some devices may also permit field upgrading of their firmware.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] For modern, simpler devices, such as USB keyboards, USB mouses and USB sound cards, the trend is to store the firmware in on-chip memory in the device's microcontroller, as opposed to storing it in a separate EEPROM chip.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Consumer products like digital cameras and portable music players support firmware upgrades.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] In digital cameras, firmware upgrades address bugs in the operation, along with adding new functions to the camera's operation.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Some companies use firmware updates to add new playable file formats (codecs).
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Other features that may change with firmware updates include the user interface or even the battery life.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Since 1996, most automobiles have employed an on-board computer and various sensors to detect mechanical problems.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] As of 2010, modern vehicles also employ computer-controlled anti-lock braking systems (ABS) and computer-operated transmission control units (TCUs).
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] The driver can also get in-dash information while driving in this manner, such as real-time fuel economy and tire pressure readings.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Local dealers can update most vehicle firmware.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Sometimes, third parties develop an unofficial new or modified ("aftermarket") version of firmware to provide new features or to unlock hidden functionality; this is referred to as custom firmware.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] An example is Rockbox as a firmware replacement for portable media players.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] There are many homebrew projects for various devices, which often unlock general-purpose computing functionality in previously limited devices (e.g., running Doom on iPods).
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Firmware hacks usually take advantage of the firmware update facility on many devices to install or run themselves.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Some, however, must resort to exploits to run, because the manufacturer has attempted to lock the hardware to stop it from running unlicensed code.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Although the Kaspersky Lab report did not explicitly claim that this group is part of the United States National Security Agency (NSA), evidence obtained from the code of various Equation Group software suggests that they are part of the NSA.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Researchers from the Kaspersky Lab categorized the undertakings by Equation Group as the most advanced hacking operation ever uncovered, also documenting around 500 infections caused by the Equation Group in at least 42 countries.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Mark Shuttleworth, the founder of the company Canonical, which created the Ubuntu Linux distribution, has described proprietary firmware as a security risk, saying that "firmware on your device is the NSA's best friend" and calling firmware "a trojan horse of monumental proportions".
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] As a potential solution to this problem, he has called for declarative firmware, which would describe "hardware linkage and dependencies" and "should not include executable code".
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Firmware should be open-source so that the code can be checked and verified.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Custom firmware hacks have also focused on injecting malware into devices such as smartphones or USB devices.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] One such smartphone injection was demonstrated on the Symbian OS at MalCon, a hacker convention.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] A USB device firmware hack called BadUSB was presented at the Black Hat USA 2014 conference, demonstrating how a USB flash drive microcontroller can be reprogrammed to spoof various other device types to take control of a computer, exfiltrate data, or spy on the user.
[src:tianocore-edk/firmware] Other security researchers have worked further on how to exploit the principles behind BadUSB, releasing at the same time the source code of hacking tools that can be used to modify the behavior of different USB devices.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] In 2004, Intel released their "Foundation Code" of their EFI implementation using a free license.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] The resulting code formed the basis of the community-run EDK project on SourceForge, started in 2004.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] The name "Tiano" was present in the initial Intel code.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] The last update to the EDK (version 1) project happened in May 2010.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] An "edk2" project was imported into SourceForge in April 2006, with a package-oriented code base again written by Intel.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] The initial "DeveloperManual" referred to this project as "Tiano R9".
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] In 2008, a stable, validated version of EDK II was tagged as "UEFI Development Kit 2008" (UDK2008).
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] The tag includes a BuildNotes.txt dating to November 2006 describing the code found in the initial import, and a BuildNotes2.txt describing modules added in May 2008.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] UDK2010 was the first version of EDK II to be widely known.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] Intel would continue to validate certain snapshots of EDK II as UDK until 2018, when EDK II moved into a "stable tag" format.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] In December 2023 a vulnerability termed "LogoFAIL" was discovered associated with EDK II which enabled an attacker to insert their own code in place of custom boot logo bitmap loader modules.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] Although EDK II implements the UEFI specification, it is not endorsed by the UEFI Forum.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] EDK II code has been integrated into other projects.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] When a specific UEFI vendor does not provide a UEFI shell, the one from TianoCore can be used.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] Google uses a version of coreboot modified to launch Tiano.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] This feature is called PIANO (payload into Tiano) or tianocoreboot.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] PIANO code was merged into coreboot in 2013.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] The code was updated to be compatible with EDK II in 2017.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] EDK II source code includes instructions for building as a payload for coreboot or Intel's "slim bootloader".
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] Project Mu is a fork of EDK II by Microsoft.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] It is an open source release of the UEFI core used in Microsoft Surface and Hyper-V products initiated by Microsoft in December 2018.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] The project promotes the idea of firmware as a service.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] The project was started to build on TianoCore's EDK II implementation to improve modularity and increase the quality of tests when building UEFI firmware.
[src:tianocore-edk/tianocore] EFIDroid is a bootloader for Android devices based on Snapdragon processors that is based on EDK II.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] UEFI replaces the BIOS that was present in the boot ROM of all personal computers that are IBM PC compatible, although it can provide backwards compatibility with the BIOS using CSM booting.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Unlike the BIOS, which was originally developed by IBM as a proprietary architecture, the UEFI specification is managed by an industry consortium.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Most production firmware implementations for both remain proprietary.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Intel developed the original *Extensible Firmware Interface* (*EFI*) specification.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The last Intel version of EFI was 1.10 released in 2005.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Subsequent versions have been developed as UEFI by the UEFI Forum.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] UEFI is independent of platform and programming language, but C is used for the reference implementation TianoCore EDKII.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The original motivation for EFI came during early development of the first Intel–HP Itanium systems in the mid-1990s.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] BIOS limitations had become too restrictive for the larger server platforms for which Itanium was targeted.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The effort to address these concerns began in 1998 and was initially called *Intel Boot Initiative*.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] It was later renamed to *Extensible Firmware Interface* (EFI).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The first open-source UEFI implementation, Tiano, was released by Intel in 2004.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Tiano has since then been superseded by EDK and EDK II and is now maintained by the TianoCore community.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In July 2008, Intel ceased its development of the EFI specification at version 1.10 and contributed it to the Unified EFI Forum, which has developed the specification as the *Unified Extensible Firmware Interface* (UEFI).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The original EFI specification remains owned by Intel, which exclusively provides licenses for EFI-based products, but the UEFI specification is owned by the UEFI Forum.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Version 2.0 of the UEFI specification was released on 31 January 2006.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Version 2.1 of the UEFI specification was released on 7 January 2007.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] It added network authentication and the user interface architecture ("Human Interface Infrastructure" in UEFI).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Version 2.3.1 of the UEFI specification was released on 6 April 2011.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] It added Secure Boot, as well as ARM architecture support.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In October 2018, Arm introduced Arm ServerReady, a compliance certification program intended to ensure standard operating systems and hypervisors run on Arm-based servers.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The program requires the system firmware to comply with Server Base Boot Requirements (SBBR).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] SBBR requires UEFI, ACPI and SMBIOS compliance.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In October 2020, Arm announced the extension of the program to the edge and IoT market.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The new program name is Arm SystemReady.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Many Linux and BSD distributions can support both recipes.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In December 2018, Microsoft announced Project Mu, a fork of TianoCore EDK II used in Microsoft Surface and Hyper-V products.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The project incorporates a service-based firmware delivery model.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The latest UEFI specification, version 2.11, was published in December 2024.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] UEFI supports processor architectures that are 32-bit or higher.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] However, only processors with a little-endian mode are supported.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Unofficial UEFI support is under development for POWERPC64 by implementing TianoCore EDK II on top of OPAL, the OpenPOWER abstraction layer, running in little-endian mode.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] For MIPS, there also exists an unofficial project, based on the original EDK.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] However, both projects have since been abandoned as of November 2016 and September 2015 respectively.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] UEFI only allows executing UEFI applications that match the firmware's bit-width, even if the processor supports smaller or larger bit-widths.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] For example, a 64-bit UEFI firmware may only execute 64-bit UEFI applications, even if the processor has a 32-bit processor mode.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Some low-end computers have been shipped with 32-bit UEFI firmware running on 64-bit CPUs.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Once a UEFI application ends the boot services and gets granted full control over the system, it becomes possible to change the processor execution mode.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] However, calling runtime services requires shortly changing back to the original processor mode, as runtime services may only be called from the same processor mode as the firmware implementation.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The Linux kernel added support for booting 64-bit kernels on 32-bit UEFI firmware implementations with x86-64 CPUs since version 3.15, requiring the UEFI boot loader to support the EFI handover protocol.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The EFI handover protocol allows UEFI boot loaders to defer the UEFI initialization to the kernel's EFI boot stub, so that only the kernel does the UEFI initialization.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In addition to the standard PC disk partition scheme that uses a master boot record (MBR), UEFI also works with the GUID Partition Table (GPT) partitioning scheme, which is free from many of the limitations of MBR.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In particular, the MBR limits on the number and size of disk partitions (up to four primary partitions per disk, and up to 2 TB (2 × 240 bytes) per disk) are relaxed.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] More specifically, GPT allows for a maximum disk and partition size of 8 ZiB (8 × 270 bytes) with 512 byte sectors.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The UEFI specification only supports FAT12/16/32 partitions that are on GPT or MBR disks as well as El Torito-formatted optical discs.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Although GPT is a part of the UEFI standard, it may also be usable by BIOS PCs to boot an operating system off of.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Support for GPT in Linux is enabled by turning on the option `CONFIG_EFI_PARTITION` (EFI GUID Partition Support) during kernel configuration.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] This option allows Linux to recognize and use GPT disks after the system firmware passes control over the system to Linux.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] For reverse compatibility, Linux can use GPT disks in BIOS-based systems for both data storage and booting, as both GRUB 2 and Linux are GPT-aware.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Such a setup is usually referred to as *BIOS-GPT*.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] As GPT incorporates the protective MBR, a BIOS-based computer can boot from a GPT disk using a GPT-aware boot loader stored in the protective MBR's bootstrap code area.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In the case of GRUB, such a configuration requires a BIOS boot partition for GRUB to embed its second-stage code due to absence of the post-MBR gap in GPT partitioned disks (which is taken over by the GPT's *Primary Header* and *Primary Partition Table*).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Commonly 1 MB in size, this partition's Globally Unique Identifier (GUID) in GPT scheme is 21686148-6449-6E6F-744E-656564454649 and is used by GRUB only in BIOS-GPT setups.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] From GRUB's perspective, no such partition type exists in case of MBR partitioning.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] This partition is not required if the system is UEFI-based because no embedding of the second-stage code is needed in that case.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] UEFI systems can access GPT disks and boot directly from them, which allows Linux to use UEFI boot methods.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Booting Linux from GPT disks on UEFI systems involves creation of an EFI system partition (ESP), which contains UEFI applications such as bootloaders, operating system kernels, and utility software.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Such a setup is usually referred to as *UEFI-GPT*, while ESP is recommended to be at least 512 MB in size and formatted with a FAT32 filesystem for maximum compatibility.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] For backward compatibility, some UEFI implementations also support booting from MBR-partitioned disks through the Compatibility Support Module (CSM) that provides legacy BIOS compatibility.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In that case, booting Linux on UEFI systems is the same as on legacy BIOS-based systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Windows 11, 64-bit versions of Windows Vista SP1/SP2 and 7, and both 32-bit and 64-bit versions of Windows 8, 8.1, and 10 can boot from a GPT disk that is larger than 2 TB.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] EFI defines two types of services: *boot services* and *runtime services*.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Boot services are available only while the firmware owns the platform (i.e., before the `ExitBootServices()` call), and they include text and graphical consoles on various devices, and bus, block and file services.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Runtime services are still accessible while the operating system is running; they include services such as date, time and NVRAM access.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] UEFI variables provide a way to store data, in particular non-volatile data.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Some UEFI variables are shared between platform firmware and operating systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Variable namespaces are identified by GUIDs, and variables are key/value pairs.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] after a crash for the operating system to retrieve after a reboot.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] UEFI executes independent programs known as UEFI applications, which are stored as files on the EFI system partition.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] These can be launched via the UEFI Shell, the firmware boot manager, or other UEFI applications, and may be developed independently of the original equipment manufacturer (OEM).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] A type of UEFI application is an OS boot loader such as GRUB, rEFInd, systemd-boot, and Windows Boot Manager, which loads some OS files into memory and executes them.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Also, an OS boot loader can provide a user interface to allow the selection of another UEFI application to run.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Utilities like the UEFI Shell are also UEFI applications.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] EFI defines protocols as a set of software interfaces used for communication between two binary modules.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] All EFI drivers must provide services to others via protocols.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The EFI Protocols are similar to the BIOS interrupt calls.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In addition to standard instruction set architecture-specific device drivers, EFI provides for an ISA-independent device driver stored in non-volatile memory as *EFI byte code* or *EBC*.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] System firmware has an interpreter for EBC images.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In that sense, EBC is analogous to Open Firmware, the ISA-independent firmware used in PowerPC-based Apple Macintosh and Sun Microsystems SPARC computers, among others.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Some architecture-specific (non-EFI Byte Code) EFI drivers for some device types can have interfaces for use by the OS.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] This allows the OS to rely on EFI for drivers to perform basic graphics and network functions before, and if, operating-system-specific drivers are loaded.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In other cases, the EFI driver can be filesystem drivers that allow for booting from other types of disk volumes.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Examples include *efifs* for 37 file systems (based on GRUB2 code), used by Rufus for chain-loading NTFS ESPs.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The EFI 1.0 specification defined a UGA (Universal Graphic Adapter) protocol as a way to support graphics features.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] UEFI did not include UGA and replaced it with GOP (Graphics Output Protocol).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] UEFI 2.1 defined a "Human Interface Infrastructure" (HII) to manage user input, localized strings, fonts, and forms (in the HTML sense).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] These enable original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) or independent BIOS vendors (IBVs) to design graphical interfaces for pre-boot configuration.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] UEFI uses UTF-16 to encode strings by default; since at least UEFI 2.4, it allows using ASCII to encode ASCII-only strings.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Most early UEFI firmware implementations were console-based.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Today many UEFI firmware implementations are GUI-based.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] An EFI system partition, often abbreviated to ESP, is a data storage device partition that is used in computers adhering to the UEFI specification.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Accessed by the UEFI firmware when a computer is powered up, it stores UEFI applications and the files these applications need to run, including operating system boot loaders.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Supported partition table schemes include MBR and GPT, as well as El Torito volumes on optical discs.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] For use on ESPs, UEFI defines a specific version of the FAT file system, which is maintained as part of the UEFI specification and independently from the original FAT specification, encompassing the FAT32, FAT16 and FAT12 file systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The ESP also provides space for a boot sector as part of the backward BIOS compatibility.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Computers are started up by a process which has been called booting: the computer loads its operating software by means of a very small program built into the hardware, which typically loads a program, still small, to load and start the operating system (OS).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Unlike the legacy PC BIOS, UEFI does not rely on boot sectors on the computer's data storage, defining instead a boot manager as part of the UEFI specification.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] When a computer is powered on, the boot manager checks the boot configuration and, based on its settings, then executes the specified OS boot loader or operating system kernel.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The boot configuration is defined by variables stored in the computer's persistent NVRAM storage, including variables that indicate the file system paths to OS loaders or OS kernels.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] OS boot loaders can be automatically detected by UEFI, which enables easy booting from removable devices such as USB flash drives.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] This automated detection relies on standardized file paths to the OS boot loader, with the path varying depending on the computer architecture.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The format of the file path is defined as <EFI_SYSTEM_PARTITION>\EFI\BOOT\BOOT<MACHINE_TYPE_SHORT_NAME>.EFI; for example, the file path to the OS loader on an x86-64 system is \efi\boot\bootx64.efi, and \efi\boot\bootaa64.efi on ARM64 architecture.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Booting UEFI systems from GPT-partitioned disks is commonly called *UEFI-GPT booting*, although the UEFI specification requires MBR partition tables to be fully supported.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Some UEFI firmware implementations immediately switch to BIOS-based CSM booting depending on the type of the boot disk's partition table, effectively preventing UEFI booting from an EFI System Partition on MBR-partitioned disks; such a boot scheme is commonly called *UEFI-MBR*.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] It is also common for a boot manager to have a textual user interface to allow the user to select the desired OS (or setup utility) from a list of available boot options.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] On PC platforms, firmware supporting UEFI boot is often referred to as a "UEFI BIOS", though some newer x86 platforms exclude CSM support entirely.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] To ensure backward compatibility, UEFI firmware implementations on PC-class machines could support booting in legacy BIOS mode from MBR-partitioned disks through the Compatibility Support Module (CSM) that provides legacy BIOS compatibility.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In this scenario, booting is performed in the same way as on legacy BIOS-based systems, by ignoring the partition table and relying on the content of a boot sector.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The Compatibility Support Module allows legacy operating systems and some legacy option ROMs that do not support UEFI to still be used.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] It also provides required legacy System Management Mode (SMM) functionality (CompatibilitySmm) in addition to features provided by the UEFI SMM.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] An example of such a legacy SMM functionality is providing USB legacy support for keyboard and mouse, by emulating their classic PS/2 counterparts.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In November 2017, Intel announced that it planned to phase out support CSM for client platforms by 2020.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In July 2022, Kaspersky Labs published information regarding a Rootkit designed to chain boot malicious code on machines using Intel's H81 chipset and the Compatibility Support Module of affected motherboards.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In August 2023, Intel announced that it planned to phase out CSM support for server platforms by 2024.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The UEFI specification includes support for booting over network via the Preboot Execution Environment (PXE).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] PXE booting network protocols include Internet Protocol (IPv4 and IPv6), User Datagram Protocol (UDP), Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP), Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) and iSCSI.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] OS images can be remotely stored on storage area networks (SANs), with Internet Small Computer System Interface (iSCSI) and Fibre Channel over Ethernet (FCoE) as supported protocols for accessing the SANs.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Version 2.5 of the UEFI specification adds support for accessing boot images over HTTP.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The UEFI specification defines a Secure Boot that can secure the boot process by preventing the loading of UEFI drivers or OS boot loaders that are not signed with an acceptable digital signature.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] When Secure Boot is enabled, it is initially placed in "setup" mode, which allows a public key known as the "platform key" (PK) to be written to the firmware.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Once the key is written, Secure Boot enters "User" mode, where only UEFI drivers and OS boot loaders signed with the platform key can be loaded by the firmware.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Additional "key exchange keys" (KEK) can be added to a database stored in memory to allow other certificates to be used, but they must still have a connection to the private portion of the platform key.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Secure Boot can also be placed in "Custom" mode, where additional public keys can be added to the system that do not match the private key.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] As of January 2025, FreeBSD support is in its planning stage.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] UEFI provides a shell environment, which can be used to execute other UEFI applications, including UEFI boot loaders.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Source code for a UEFI shell can be downloaded from the Intel's TianoCore UDK/EDK2 project.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] A pre-built ShellBinPkg is also available.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Shell v2 works best in UEFI 2.3+ systems and is recommended over Shell v1 in those systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Shell v1 should work in all UEFI systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Methods used for launching UEFI shell depend on the manufacturer and model of the system motherboard.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Some of them already provide a direct option in firmware setup for launching, e.g. compiled x86-64 version of the shell needs to be made available as `<EFI_SYSTEM_PARTITION>/SHELLX64.EFI`.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Some other systems have an already embedded UEFI shell which can be launched by appropriate key press combinations.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] For other systems, the solution is either creating an appropriate USB flash drive or adding manually (`bcfg`) a boot option associated with the compiled version of shell.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The following is a list of commands supported by the EFI shell.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Extensions to UEFI can be loaded from virtually any non-volatile storage device attached to the computer.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] For example, an original equipment manufacturer (OEM) can distribute systems with an EFI system partition on the hard drive, which would add additional functions to the standard UEFI firmware stored on the motherboard's ROM.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] UEFI Capsule defines a firmware-to-OS firmware update interface.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Windows 8, Windows 8.1, Windows 10, and Fwupd for Linux each support the UEFI Capsule.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Like BIOS, UEFI initializes and tests system hardware components, and then loads the boot loader from a mass storage device or through a network connection.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In x86 systems, the UEFI firmware is usually stored in the NOR flash chip of the motherboard, and the boot process is more complex, for example PCI Express devices detection and initialization.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In some ARM-based Android and Windows Phone devices, the UEFI boot loader is stored in the eMMC or eUFS flash memory.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Starting from the 10th Gen Intel Core, Intel no longer provides Legacy Video BIOS for the iGPU (Intel Graphics Technology).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Legacy boot with those CPUs requires a Legacy Video BIOS, which can still be provided by a video card.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] This is the first stage of the UEFI boot but may have platform specific binary code that precedes it.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] (e.g., Intel ME, AMD PSP, CPU microcode).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] It consists of minimal code written in assembly language for the specific architecture.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] It initializes a temporary memory (often CPU cache-as-RAM (CAR), or SoC on-chip boot processor) and serves as the system's software root of trust with the option of verifying PEI before hand-off.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The second stage of UEFI boot consists of a dependency-aware dispatcher that loads and runs PEI modules (PEIMs) to handle early hardware initialization tasks such as main memory initialization (initialize memory controller and DRAM) and firmware recovery operations.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Additionally, it is responsible for discovery of the current boot mode and handling many ACPI S3 operations.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In the case of ACPI S3 resume, it is responsible for restoring many hardware registers to a pre-sleep state.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Initialization at this stage involves creating data structures in memory and establishing default values within these structures.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] This stage has several components including PEI foundation, PEIMs and PPI.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Due to less resources available in this stage, this stage must be minimal and do minimal preparations for the next stage, DXE, which is richer.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] After SEC phase hand off, platform responsibility is taken by PEI Foundation.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] This component is responsible for invoking PEIMs and managing their dependencies.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] These are minimal PEI drivers that are responsible for initialization of hardware components, such as permanent memory, CPU, chipset and motherboard.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Each of the PEIMs have single responsibilities and focus on single initialization.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] These drivers come from different vendors.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] This is a data structure that composed of GUID pairs of pointers.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] PPIs are discovered by PEIMs through PEI services.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] After minimal initialization of the system for DXE, PEI foundation locates and passes control to DXE.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The PEI foundation dispatches DXE foundation through special PPI called IPL (Initial Program Load).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] This stage consists of C modules and a dependency-aware dispatcher.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] With main memory now available, CPU, chipset, mainboard and other I/O devices are initialized in DXE and BDS.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Initialization at this stage involves assigning EFI device paths to the hardware connected to the motherboard, and transferring configuration data to the hardware.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In this stage, boot devices are initialized, UEFI drivers or Option ROMs of PCI devices are executed according to architecturally defined variables called **NVRAM**, and the operating system boot loaders (such as Windows Boot Manager) are started.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] This is the stage between boot device selection and hand-off to the OS.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] At this point one may enter a UEFI shell, or execute a UEFI application such as the OS boot loader.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The UEFI hands off to the operating system (OS) after ExitBootServices() is executed.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] A UEFI compatible OS is now responsible for exiting boot services triggering the firmware to unload all no longer needed code and data, leaving only runtime services code/data, e.g.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] A typical modern OS will prefer to use its own programs (such as kernel drivers) to control hardware devices.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] When a legacy OS is used, CSM will handle this call ensuring the system is compatible with legacy BIOS expectations.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Intel's implementation of EFI is the *Intel Platform Innovation Framework*, codenamed *Tiano*.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Tiano runs on Intel's XScale, Itanium, IA-32 and x86-64 processors, and is proprietary software, although a portion of the code has been released under the BSD license or Eclipse Public License (EPL) as TianoCore EDK II.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] TianoCore can be used as a payload for coreboot.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Phoenix Technologies' implementation of UEFI is branded as SecureCore Technology (SCT).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] American Megatrends offers its own UEFI firmware implementation known as Aptio, while Insyde Software offers InsydeH2O, and Byosoft offers ByoCore.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In December 2018, Microsoft released an open source version of its TianoCore EDK2-based UEFI implementation from the Surface line, Project Mu.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] An implementation of the UEFI API was introduced into the Universal Boot Loader (Das U-Boot) in 2017.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] On the ARMv8 architecture Linux distributions use the U-Boot UEFI implementation in conjunction with GNU GRUB for booting (e.g.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] SUSE Linux), the same holds true for OpenBSD.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] For booting from iSCSI iPXE can be used as a UEFI application loaded by U-Boot.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Intel's first Itanium workstations and servers, released in 2000, implemented EFI 1.02.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Hewlett-Packard's first Itanium 2 systems, released in 2002, implemented EFI 1.10.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] These systems were able to boot Windows, Linux, FreeBSD and HP-UX.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] OpenVMS added UEFI capability in June 2003.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In January 2006, Apple Inc. shipped its first Intel-based Macintosh computers.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] These systems used EFI instead of Open Firmware, which had been used on its previous PowerPC-based systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] On 5 April 2006, Apple first released Boot Camp, which produces a Windows drivers disk and a non-destructive partitioning tool to allow the installation of Windows XP or Vista without requiring a reinstallation of Mac OS X (now macOS).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] A firmware update was also released that added BIOS compatibility to its EFI implementation.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Subsequent Macintosh models shipped with the newer firmware.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] During 2005, more than one million Intel systems shipped with Intel's implementation of UEFI.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] New mobile, desktop and server products, using Intel's implementation of UEFI, started shipping in 2006.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] For instance, boards that use the Intel 945 chipset series use Intel's UEFI firmware implementation.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Since 2005, EFI has also been implemented on non-PC architectures, such as embedded systems based on XScale cores.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The EDK (EFI Developer Kit) includes an NT32 target, which allows EFI firmware and EFI applications to run within a Windows application.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] However, no direct hardware access is allowed by EDK NT32.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] This means only a subset of EFI application and drivers can be executed by the EDK NT32 target.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In 2008, more x86-64 systems adopted UEFI.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] While many of these systems still allow booting only the BIOS-based OSes via the Compatibility Support Module (CSM) (thus not appearing to the user to be UEFI-based), other systems started to allow booting UEFI-based OSes.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] For example, IBM x3450 server, MSI motherboards with ClickBIOS and HP EliteBook Notebook PCs.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In 2009, IBM shipped System x machines (x3550 M2, x3650 M2, iDataPlex dx360 M2) and BladeCenter HS22 with UEFI capability.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Dell shipped PowerEdge T610, R610, R710, M610 and M710 servers with UEFI capability.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] More commercially available systems are mentioned in a UEFI whitepaper.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In 2011, major vendors (such as ASRock, Asus, Gigabyte, and MSI) launched several consumer-oriented motherboards using the Intel 6-series LGA 1155 chipset and AMD 9 Series AM3+ chipsets with UEFI.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] With the release of Windows 8 in October 2012, Microsoft's certification requirements now require that computers include firmware that implements the UEFI specification.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Furthermore, if the computer supports the "Connected Standby" feature of Windows 8 (which allows devices to have power management comparable to smartphones, with an almost instantaneous return from standby mode), then the firmware is not permitted to contain a Compatibility Support Module (CSM).
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] As such, systems that support Connected Standby are incapable of booting Legacy BIOS operating systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In October 2017, Intel announced that it would remove legacy PC BIOS support from all its products by 2020, in favor of UEFI Class 3.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] By 2019, all computers based on Intel platforms no longer have legacy PC BIOS support.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] A operating system that can be booted from (U)EFI is called a (U)EFI-aware operating system, defined by (U)EFI specification.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Here the term *booted from a (U)EFI* means directly booting the system using a (U)EFI operating system loader stored on any storage device.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The default location for the operating system loader is `<EFI_SYSTEM_PARTITION>/BOOT/BOOT<MACHINE_TYPE_SHORT_NAME>.EFI`, where short name of the machine type can be `IA32`, `X64`, `IA64`, `ARM` or `AA64`.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Some operating systems vendors may have their own boot loaders.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] They may also change the default boot location.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] UEFI implementation flaws have been exploited to gain persistence, the ability to maintain malicious access to a compromised system even after system reboot, operating system reinstallation, and even partial physical part replacement, such as of corrupted PCI persistent flash storage.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] There were vulnerabilities in 2023 even with Secure Boot enabled.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In 2023 Microsoft published a warning about BlackLotus UEFI malware.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Numerous digital rights activists have protested UEFI.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Minnich, a co-author of coreboot, and Cory Doctorow, a digital rights activist, have criticized UEFI as an attempt to remove the ability of the user to truly control the computer.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Critics, such as coreboot co-author Ronald G.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Minnich, argue that UEFI maintains the historic arrangement of requiring two separate drivers—one for the firmware and one for the operating system—for most hardware.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Open-source project TianoCore also provides UEFIs.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] TianoCore lacks the specialized firmware drivers and modules that initialize chipset functions, but TianoCore is one of many payload options of coreboot.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] The development of coreboot requires cooperation from chipset manufacturers to provide the specifications needed to develop initialization drivers.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In 2011, Microsoft announced that computers certified to run its Windows 8 operating system had to ship with Microsoft's public key enrolled and Secure Boot enabled, which implies that using UEFI is a requirement for these devices.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Following the announcement, critics and free-software/open-source advocates, including the Free Software Foundation, expressed concern that Microsoft might use the Secure Boot functionality of UEFI to restrict the installation of alternative operating systems such as Linux.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Microsoft denied that the Secure Boot requirement was intended to serve as a form of lock-in and clarified its requirements by stating that x86-based systems certified for Windows 8 must allow Secure Boot to enter custom mode or be disabled, but not on systems using the ARM architecture.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Windows 10 allows OEMs to decide whether or not Secure Boot can be managed by users of their x86 systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Other developers raised concerns about the legal and practical issues of implementing support for Secure Boot on Linux systems in general.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Other developers suggested that signed builds of Linux with another key could be provided, but noted that it would be difficult to persuade OEMs to ship their computers with the required key alongside the Microsoft key.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Several major Linux distributions have developed different implementations for Secure Boot.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Garrett himself developed a minimal bootloader known as a shim, which is a precompiled, signed bootloader that allows the user to individually trust keys provided by Linux distributions.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] That also allows users to build their own kernels and use custom kernel modules as well, without the need to reconfigure the system.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Fedora also uses shim, but requires that both the kernel and its modules be signed as well. shim has Machine Owner Key (MOK) that can be used to sign locally compiled kernels and other software not signed by distribution maintainer, without changing the Secure Boot mode to setup mode.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In Windows, if Secure Boot is enabled, all kernel drivers must be digitally signed; non-WHQL drivers may be refused to load.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In February 2013, another Red Hat developer attempted to submit a patch to the Linux kernel that would allow it to parse Microsoft's authenticode signing using a master X.509 key embedded in PE files signed by Microsoft.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] However, the proposal was criticized by Linux creator Linus Torvalds, who argued that Red Hat was accommodating Microsoft's control over the Secure Boot infrastructure.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] On 26 March 2013, the Spanish free-software development group Hispalinux filed a formal complaint with the European Commission, contending that Microsoft's Secure Boot requirements on OEM systems were "obstructive" and anti-competitive.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] At the Black Hat conference in August 2013, a group of security researchers presented a series of exploits in specific vendor implementations of UEFI that could be used to exploit Secure Boot.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In August 2016 it was reported that two security researchers had found the "golden key" security key Microsoft uses in signing operating systems.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Technically, no key was exposed, but an exploitable binary signed by the key was.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] This allows software to execute as though it were signed by Microsoft, presenting potential risks for rootkit and bootkit attacks.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] This also complicates remediation efforts, since a patch can potentially be downgraded by replacing it with the signed exploitable binary.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Microsoft stated that the vulnerability only affects ARM architecture and Windows RT devices and released two updates; however, reports noted that these updates do not completely prevent exploitation because fully resolving the vulnerability would require key replacements in end-user firmware.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] On 1 March 2023, researchers from ESET reported discovering "BlackLotus", described as the first active UEFI bootkit capable of bypassing UEFI Secure Boot by exploiting the limitations of the previous security updates.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In August 2024, the Windows 11 and Windows 10 security updates applied the Secure Boot Advanced Targeting (SBAT) settings to device's UEFI NVRAM, which caused some Linux distributions to fail to load.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] SBAT is a protocol that supported in new versions of Windows Boot Manager and shim, which refuse buggy or vulnerable intermediate bootloaders (usually older versions of Windows Boot Manager and GRUB) to load in the boot process.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In June 2025, LWN.net reported that the Microsoft UEFI CA 2011 certificate will be expired on June 27, 2026, which may refuse some Linux to load if Secure Boot is enabled.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] However, in TianoCore EDK II as well as many commercial UEFI implementations (such as AMI Aptio), time/date check for Secure Boot certificate is usually disabled by default.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Many Linux distributions support UEFI Secure Boot as of January 2025, such as RHEL (RHEL 7 and later), CentOS (CentOS 7 and later), Ubuntu, Fedora, Debian (Debian 10 and later), OpenSUSE, and SUSE Linux Enterprise.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] A number of technical issues have been reported regarding specific implementations of UEFI firmware in commercial devices.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] Similar operational difficulties were reported regarding several Toshiba laptop models where specific firmware certificates required for Secure Boot operation were missing.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] In January 2013, a firmware issue was publicized regarding the UEFI implementation on certain Samsung laptops, which rendered the devices completely inoperable after a Linux distribution was installed in UEFI mode.
[src:tianocore-edk/uefi] His analysis concluded that the associated kernel module caused kernel message dumps to be written to the firmware storage space, executing the failure state.
